[7]: Because seriously what else do you hold in games? Paper is so lame.
[8]: Turing machines are the simplest possible computers. 

Say you have a long strip of paper with letters on it - A, B, whatever. You have a little computer above a certain position on the strip. It can do any of the following actions, but only one at a time:

* Move the strip back or forth
* Check the current letter on the strip
* Write a new letter on the strip. 

From that, you can solve any problem that the big fancy computer you have at home can. It is really quite humbling.

[9]: The Fermi Problem is this: Given the universe is unfathomably vast, and alien life must have arisen somewhere, why has none of it tried to contact us? 

[10]: In text based adventure games of yore, the adventurer would be provided with a description of where they are (like: You enter the dungeon. You see a flickering light off in the distance.), and a prompt: >>. Players type their action (like: Follow light) after the >>, the game outputs a new description and a prompt, and so on.

[11]: His favorite drink.
[12]: The Game provides Players with Heads Up Displays. Imagine having useful information overlayed over your vision. Jane has small lights indicating when her friends have logged on.
[13]: Lucida Handwriting looks like this: http://www.clickstart.org.uk/assets/img/sites/pages/5906/LucidaHandwriting.gif
[14]: Georgia looks like this: ((TODO - could just provide an example right in the text.))
[15]: Or even realize.
[16]: Although VeraGames uses writers and artists as examples of occuptations, creative pursuits comprise a relatively small minority of the Realm.

======

[i1]: A murder in the Realm is not permanent as is murder in Real Life. But it was determined that death should not be without effect. Those who break the laws of the Realm should be punished accordingly. So death will terminate your current character in the Realm, but will not restrict you from making a new character. 

Permanent bans from the Realm are exceedingly rare.

[i2]: Early user testing showed that gamers preferred the physicality of the phone and the callback to Real Life, even though no such physicality was necessary. 

This is also why users must use teleportation pads - they can't just teleport willy-nilly. Testers claim it feels more _real,_ somehow.

You can't suss these feelings out, or argue against them. You just have to go with them.

[i3]: A global Realm chat was at one time open, but it became unmaintainable after around the 10k user mark. Nowadays, chat rooms are locality specific, and contain up to a few hundred people.

[i4]: Call/cc is a keyword included in most modern programming languages.

_Say you're in the kitchen in front of the refrigerator, thinking about a sandwich. You take a label right there and stick it in your pocket. Then you get some turkey and bread out of the refrigerator and make yourself a sandwich, which is now sitting on the counter. You invoke call/cc, and you find yourself standing in front of the refrigerator again, thinking about a sandwich. But fortunately, there's a sandwich on the counter, and all the materials used to make it are gone. So you eat it._

[i5]: At any given time, VeraGames has millions of servers crunching data to provide the best experience for each Player. The way that they handle something like call/cc is to temporarily speed up one player's mind by allocating it more servers. 

One of VeraGames' crucial early discoveries was that the human mind believes it has a fixed speed at which it processes information. The mind does not perceptibly speed up. Instead, the world slows down. These pseudo-relativistic effects are used to great effect in the Realm. ((lol effect!)) 

[i6]: VeraGames tries to _learn_ what game experience you would prefer, and then offer that experience to you. This may involve a few mistakes and dead ends early on in the game, but as the Game continues, it gradually comes to understand the player. 

[i7]: Driving is of course free in the Realm, apart from a one time fee to purchase the car.

((uggly)) One thing that was anticipated, but perhaps not in proper appreciation of the eventual scope, was the way that the Realm upended traditional jobs. Nearly the entire transportation industry was deprecated with Realmwide transportation.

On the other hand, The Realm created plenty of new opportunities. Lance's position is one of those rare situations where his job perfectly intersects his game scenario. 

======

[f1]: _Things he thought but did not say:_

TWO: You need to separate your consciousness, your _human_ being, if you will, from the greater universe. You must examine with a detached mind. Imagine pure deconstructionism: we are just atoms. I know you want to say: _No._ That we are something more than the sum of our parts. That we live, breathe, eat, think, dream, create. You are right. But it is not relevant. Imagine this.
TWO: Imagine the vast space of all possible goals. Imagine everything. Imagine the goal of simply hoarding as much carbon as you can. Imagine the goal of inciting certain chemical reactions within your own body. Imagine the goal of seeking out the clearest white color imaginable. Imagine being a blue minimizing robot[a]. And so forth.
TWO: Now you see this space. Now look at all the goals that humans hold. They are points of light in the darkness. Is there any rhyme or reason to their choice?
TWO: Evolution. That is the only rhyme or reason.
TWO: But evolution is just one of the many selection mechanisms along another vast darkness.
TWO: I will spare you another effete metaphor.

[a]: http://lesswrong.com/lw/6ha/the_blueminimizing_robot/ 

[f2]: 

:: It is 2034. JANE ALIAN tugs at her brother, JACK's, shirt.[a] JACK is on the computer, playing a VIDEO GAME.

"Read this book! Read this book! Common READ IT!"

Jack personally believes that she is the most annoying 9 year old ever. 

In two years, the Realm would be established. Jack started playing almost immediately when it went into beta; due to age limits Jane could not join for several years. They grew apart slowly, and a distance formed that they have since had trouble crossing.

The book was (of course) "And Then There Were None."

[a]: Jane's parents were those people who think they're really clever by giving each of their kids names that start with the same letter. The joke was on them when they had twins later on. Jane just holds out hope that their names were switched an even number of times.(())

[f3]: Dan Farrer, in Real Life, would probably find this conversation a little strange. How could Mme. Chan know who he was ahead of time? He certainly doesn't know her. He would feel that the dialog was forced.

VeraGames accommodates for the initial strangeness of the Realm by making small tweaks to a Player's mental state. See "PALAVER IS HELD... AGAIN."

[f4]: This is actually his desire, if it wasn't clear already.

[f5]: Jane only rarely slips up grammatically. Lance decides not to bring it up because she seems anxious. He instead catalogs it for later retrieval. A true friend.

